USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost strange how eagerly Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghanistan issue, whom he himself thought the dumbest.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he had been copying it on the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario for three years.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the Bush declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Way Forward" without hesitation.
He himself, three years ago, criticized the Bush idea of sending fresh troops into Iraq, which was plagued by civil war, as "irresponsible and with its consequences disastrous".
But the months that followed showed that the Bush strategy, based on military recommendations, was the only one possible and so successful that Iraq is no longer mentioned in the news.
Bush's reputation was not improved by this, for objectively he left his successor a much more grateful starting position than could have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama is hoping for a repeat of the miracle.
He was again asked by the military to increase the troop contingent, especially by the commander in chief of the Afghanistan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even criticized the hesitant gunmen in the White House despite his subordination habits.
He called for 40,000 soldiers to turn the tide.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't come up with a better idea, and so he cheated the general out of at least 10,000 soldiers.
He has pressed Europe to pledge another 5,000, even though he himself originally expected at least 10,000.
The most problematic aspect of the whole Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete this process in three years.
Some doubt that the halving of the increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the brotherly war of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-structured, its leaders honoring values.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the contraindication that no one can be trusted and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if formally correctly established, remain mere mock-ups behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balance of interests between the various ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the ambiguity of the circumstances, which further complicates the Pakistan and Iran influences.
The creation of a 'state capable of action', which is the minimalist aim of the whole operation, is also very unrealistic.
The timeline of Obama's strategy, alienated by his voluntarism
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and now it is on the verge of explosion.
To believe that the little soldiers who have broken out into the war cry about the "early return home" can create a miracle here can only a truly romantic soul, who is not impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, the date of the withdrawal of troops is irresponsible because the Taliban will take it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the European willingness to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is running out.
The European politicians cannot and will not explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war in the Indo-Cussian highlands.
Another possible factor that could radically affect the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions on the Iranians do not have an effect, the United States will have to ask itself a very serious question: can the problem not be solved with troops?
This question must be answered as the post-Obama America moves to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any solution will also mean a dramatic change in the situation in Afghanistan.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years until the presidential election, and thus enough time for him to resort to another strategy in case it proves to be a total failure.
