Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'stabilized' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent HIV from spreading in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on the viruses that are already drug resistant.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not have as strong an effect on common virus variants as one of the existing drugs.
The disease AIDS is not yet curable.
But the combination of drugs can extend the patient's life and prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
However, taking them can have a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of viral replication also leads to the development of resistant viruses against which no drugs are effective.
The work of experts from three institutes at the Academy of Sciences CR, the University of Chemical Technology Prague and Heidelberg University is paving the way for tackling virus resistance.
They have shown that substances called metallocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metallocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block viral replication in a way that is different from any drugs currently used, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
The metallocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-layered cages made of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, linked by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A Devious and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus splitting caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would be produced.
By shutting down the HIV protease, we also shut down the virus' replication in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper, published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain that is then systematically altered.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effects of these anti-HIV protease agents were tested in a test tube, including against their resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metallocarborans on the common enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinical medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity, and the possibility of further chemical configurations, make metallocarborans interesting compounds for further research into the development of effective HIV drugs, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
