Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted to ban minarets and there is widespread concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-thought-out report on whether Muslims can and are integrated into one of Europe's most secularised societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's latest work, "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and argumentative study of a controversial issue that divided and occupied the country for a decade and a half and whose effects are still felt today.
Bowen's latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He spent months in mosques, schools and institutions that now offer what Bowen calls "Islamic freedom" to the five to six million Muslims in France.
He is a good listener, he reproduces debates between teachers and students about the questions that worry them most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and gay rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane matters, he claims, that make up everyday life, in contrast to the political dramas that the media are busy with.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of whom have a well-known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss-born Arab-Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open up the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
You don't have all the arguments on your side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists interviewed by Bowen are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts - proponents of purist Sunni Islam, which is linked to Saudi Arabia - who today have a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires a give and take on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) really feel committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who in turn have had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He sees a "tightening of the screw" rather than a growing pragmatism.
After reading this book, you are inclined to say, "Yes, but not yet".
The Most Desolate Prospect in the World
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatically than any other environmental region on Earth.
The ice that marks them is melting at an alarming rate, taking with it life that can survive nowhere else.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests have recently ventured into the open waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now writers in their wake.
Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws a natural history of the icon of the North, the polar bear, in On Thin Ice.
He is well versed in the complex history and politics of whaling and describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who have proved themselves in the hunt for polar bears.
Admiral Nelson's encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old ensign at sea, fighting only with the barrel of his musket, is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance in the early 20th century featured 75 polar bears in one performance.
Even today, zoos still typically have one millionth of the range of a wild animal, and the climate is rarely suitable: the polar bear in Singapore has turned green from the algae growing in the hollow hairs of its fur.
Click here to learn more!
Ellis refers to the accounts of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America, and Russia, the hunt continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and motor sleds use powerful Inuit assault rifles to hunt their prey.
Ironically, the waters north of these two hunting nations will be the ones that will last the longest.
In his new book, "After the Ice", Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine New Scientist, offers a clear and disturbing account of Arctic science and a gripping glimpse into what the future might hold.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of the changes.
But this is not because of a lack of explanatory attempts.
The pioneering voyages of Fridtjof Nansen in the late 19th and early 20th centuries first suggested the swirling of the pack ice.
During the Cold War, submarines measured the moving reefs when they were underwater.
