UN group draws up plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference - which has so far been marked by wild poses and mutual accusations - re-focused on Friday on the release of a document that sets out an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations bearing the brunt of the burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has identified both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as a major step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time as more than 100 top politicians from around the world arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a special UN working group, omits the amount of money rich countries should give to poor countries to help them cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialized and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global temperature rise should be for policy makers to contribute.
The process will be given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, has called "the big picture".
It outlines a possible agreement whereby developed nations would jointly cut their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would cut their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, these countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also gave a boost to talks on Friday by pledging $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change, from tackling floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday, however, brought the same verbal fireworks that had dominated the talks last week.
The US climate change special envoy Todd Stern has rejected formulations that call for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared with voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, if these are not financed by the developed nations.
This move announced that the Obama administration was taking a tougher line on China than the Bush administration did less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign a deal without major emerging economies standing up and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern's remarks came an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the top US climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or was "highly irresponsible" to say earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to tackle global warming.
The future economic course of the great world powers is at stake, and this has created a rift between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current battle is about saving individual economies as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting over their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the great powers were fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, since even affected countries have moved to be more aggressive in holding countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will develop a new economic dominance, says Ulate, who is also a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most affected by climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the small island states' offensive "put political pressure on the whole political process", partly because they are now united and demanding action from emerging countries such as China and India.
The talks gained a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most outstanding issues still needed to be resolved before the leaders arrived to reach an agreement.
High-ranking officials, including India's environment minister Jairam Ramesh and China's vice minister, boarded their planes and rested in the hallways of the Bella Center for closed-door meetings and press conferences to discuss claims that will be heard over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people walking in and out of the convention center every day, activists playing guitar hosting late-night shows mocking the countries they think are betraying and selling, and draft treaties being handed out hand-to-hand instead of by email -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building: almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are coming to the top", said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
