The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The six-foot-long [2.0 m] and five-foot-tall [1.50 m] animal ran on two powerful hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-clawed claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it wouldn't have been anything special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to display these physical features, Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in the journal Science on Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the relationships, the distribution and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, unprecedented for Triassic deposits, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by the researchers as new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of five individuals.
Finding confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says it is an extraordinary find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only found in single fragments".
Other dinosaur experts don't necessarily share that enthusiasm.
This discovery is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current theory, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the classification of these ancient dinosaurs is often controversial.
For example, experts debate when lizards split into their three main evolutionary lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "long-necks", and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithischia, which included Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air sacs, similar to those of the descendants of theropods, the birds.
Thanks to air sacs, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light-weight bones, the common ancestor of both groups likely had produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers conclude that lizards first appeared there.
Thus, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America to all the continents that then formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
The team, along with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other theropods, not particularly closely related.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, a sister group of the dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
He believes that the picture may be distorted because South America has a particularly large number of primitive dinosaur fossils, while other continents have few.
How dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare side-line of the reptilian tribe into the dominant agricultural vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying dinosaurs and numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relatives on the border between the Triassic and Jurassic became extinct.
The success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction, and the dinosaurs just happened to survive, but the other reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to flourish, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had been given a shadow existence: mammals.
