The dream worlds
Some people see images and hear voices that others cannot see or hear.
It's not just the mentally ill and drug addicts who blur the lines between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in your sleep, it's okay.
When we lie with our eyes closed in our dark rooms, we are allowed to indulge in wildest imaginings and fantasies.
However, in the modern Western world, those who experience dreamlike states while awake, seeing and hearing things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered insane or drug addicted, at least as a freak.
But such images and voices are not limited to those who are mentally ill or under the influence of drugs.
It's our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes blur the lines between dream, delusion, and reality.
Dreamy altered states of waking consciousness can take many forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusions.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic raptures, psychosis, and hallucinations can all be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of the brain's neuronal messengers - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and acetylcholine - is disturbed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very common during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has intrigued philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dreaming in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 a "great similarity of insanity with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all its inconsistencies, delusions, delusions of such".
It's the fall of 2001, and Henning T. is turning into a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and crisp.
Gravity has no power over him, he's floating on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted fangs, gnashing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, malicious voices thunder from walls and radio.
He can't take it anymore, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. rips two wires from the stereo, knots them into a loop, and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He gets on a speaker and puts the noose around his neck.
Jump, now.
The noose is coming off.
Let this be a lesson to you, the voices in the drum-shredding choir shout, "go to the clinic and get cured!"
Henning T. is 40 years old today, he's had six acute psychosis episodes, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, and he's also manic-depressive, taking medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness. He's been married for three years.
"In my psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and the deepest despair", he says.
The Illusions Are Cruel Realities
About one percent of the population will have schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime, and in psychiatric hospitals it is the second most common disorder treated after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers often cannot distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, and they become hyperactive, which can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, delusions of relationship, or delusions of persecution.
Hearing voices - voices that command, comment, or dialogue - is especially common.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The sufferer is unable to separate important from unimportant, the brain is unable to filter out disturbing signals, the mind is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens the floodgates to ideas and fantasies that originate in deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subjective, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the General Psychiatry Clinic at the University Hospital Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he becomes passive, as in a dream, overwhelmed by events and unable to actively shape them.
As a result, schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
They are often unable to reconcile reality, the delusions are cruel reality, awakening is impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life.
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality perceived in psychosis is basically preserved".
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real framework.
Why our brain does such a capricious thing is still a mystery to researchers.
Exceptional circumstances can cause any person to lose touch with reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers believe that the brain damage is minimal.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains a mystery how the disruption of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself for many years at first.
Environmental factors also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are running hot
The crazy thing is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others spend money on drugs to get them, says Erich Kasten, a professor of psychology in L√ºbeck.
Whether delusions are pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of viewpoint.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he published his findings in the book The Unreal World in Our Mind.
Although hallucinations are a common symptom of psychosis, they are also a common symptom of many other disorders.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression, but often include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease, and traumatic brain injury.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate.
Hallucinations, says Kasten, are made up of memory contents that are usually withheld.
They occur when areas of the brain that process sensory perception are over- or under-activated, when our brains are running hot, or when there is a lack of stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But it's also a symptom of withdrawal, stress, heartbreak, or other mental disorders.
In recent studies, up to a third of those surveyed reported experiencing hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends high school there.
A very normal girl, actually.
If it wasn't for the images and the voices.
During the break, a sloppy boy with long, dark hair may address it.
When he answers, the classmates look at him in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
You think the shy girl is a crazy daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
She's awake, she hears and sees this boy, just like she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she wonders sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other delusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
Often, the delusions are also a burden.
When she is in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the lesson because the teacher is introducing a new classmate to her eyes and ears while he explains mathematical equations audibly and visually on the blackboard to everyone else.
At night, the apparitions are usually scary.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes far too seldom and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees, the freckles or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, are coming before her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she shouts at the figures.
She won't tell her parents or friends, they'll think she's crazy.
It's the fall of 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from withdrawal, they are more likely to hallucinate after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is under-employed and is taking care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when, at age 13, she learned that the man she's called Dad since she can remember was not her biological father.
Because visual and auditory hallucinations involve the same brain regions that process real-world impressions and sounds, sufferers like Sarah K. have difficulty distinguishing between delusions and reality. "Every experience", says Kasten, "is in the brain, where reality is represented.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real".
Night vision is also valued by Kasten as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to value hallucinations as a special ability.
The borderline between dream and hallucination
In our world, which is too consciously centered, imaginary experiences are unfortunately often pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician of the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in D√ºsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also carries positive, creative traits - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has been researching the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer believes to be real and that he cannot distinguish from the waking state even afterwards.
Oneiroid state of consciousness occurs in extreme situations due to trauma or disease, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
When a person is threatened with loss of self and the world, such as by a persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening reality with his own imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
It's like a borderline between a dream and a hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is made present in the imagination.
An intense form of meaning and meaning-making in an inherently intolerable situation, which allows us humans our own capacity to design, not to sink into a void of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Switch" as a soul-saving action.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness is taken away after heart valve surgery and subsequent heart transplant, and he travels for days while his body is condemned to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created himself, visiting strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make drugs out of blood.
He's kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle back to his homeland, surfing the snow-covered Alps with his hospital bed, and meets a Korean mobster.
It's completely absorbed in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different for Claussen from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories of mental travel are still vivid to me years later, in subtle detail.
More vivid and intense than anything you've ever actually experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows the horizon of our other life experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug addiction show how fragile our inner images of external reality are even when awake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality".
An experience that can be very enriching.
