75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their maternity
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study on fertility and career development of women in Spain, carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working women feel that their career prospects on the labour market are restricted by their maternity.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children depending on whether women work or not and, if so, what kind of work they do.
Those who do not work outside the home, work only part-time or have no fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with permanent jobs, especially in the public sector, postpone starting a family and becoming mothers and therefore have fewer children.
"Women aged 35-49 with a permanent job have their first child on average 3.7 years after moving in, a figure which rises to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job who have taken longer to achieve this and who have not had their move in and their first child until much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major impact on motherhood, although less than the calendar in terms of pregnancy readiness", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor to be taken into account in the age of women at marriage and first child.
The survey shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which the couple marries and has their first child.
This difference was also observed in women of the same age.
For example, women in the 35-49 age group, depending on whether they have only a high school diploma or higher education, became mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 or 32.1 years.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While women with a bachelor's degree get married and have their first child before they start their first permanent job, women with a high school diploma or higher do the opposite, first finding a permanent job and then getting married and having their first child, Delgado notes.
