Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as is now the case with the ESP stability control, the emergency braking systems must become a mandatory feature in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while a grace period has been set for the remaining vehicles until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's decision is intended to improve pedestrian protection, but these braking systems can also help prevent many accidents because of their operation.
The function of the emergency brake assist is to increase the pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects by the brake force applied by the driver on the brake pedal.
But this system does not exert that pressure to the end.
According to a study commissioned by the Bosch vehicle component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not brake with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake assist, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force into the braking system, reducing the braking time and thus the braking distance a car travels during braking.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
Even fewer accidents - one in four accidents with injuries is expected to be prevented - once so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then fitted with a system that detects obstacles (by radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while applying a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver responds, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning, even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant shall apply maximum pressure to the brakes to minimise the damage.
